WEBVTT

00:01.482 --> 00:03.103
Adult Dean: One thing that
all species have in common

00:03.103 --> 00:05.103
is that at some point,
offspring have to leave

00:05.103 --> 00:07.827
the protection of their parents
and venture out on their own.

00:08.862 --> 00:10.413
The process
of gaining independence

00:10.413 --> 00:12.551
can go smoothly...

00:12.551 --> 00:15.793
or not smoothly at all.

00:17.103 --> 00:18.379
Um...

00:18.379 --> 00:20.103
I was wondering,

00:20.103 --> 00:22.413
can I go to the mall
with some kids from my school?

00:22.413 --> 00:23.689
"Who's gonna be there?"

00:23.689 --> 00:25.068
"What are their parents'
names?"

00:25.068 --> 00:26.241
"Why do you want
to go there anyway?"

00:26.241 --> 00:27.862
"We got popcorn at the house."
"Do you have mall money?"

00:28.482 --> 00:30.689
Unfortunately,
my parents were not the kind

00:30.689 --> 00:32.758
to just let their kids
hang out at the mall,

00:32.758 --> 00:34.482
even after it was desegregated.

00:35.931 --> 00:37.931
When I was a kid,
the Nordale Mall

00:37.931 --> 00:39.793
was like Mecca,
the Promised Land,

00:39.793 --> 00:41.724
and the Forbidden City
all in one.

00:41.724 --> 00:44.172
It had delicious food,
sharp clothes,

00:44.172 --> 00:46.172
and a pet store full
of puppies.

00:46.172 --> 00:48.034
But most of all,
it had teenagers

00:48.034 --> 00:51.310
having the time of their lives
totally unsupervised.

00:51.310 --> 00:53.034
I couldn't wait
to hang out at the mall

00:53.034 --> 00:55.448
without having my parents
dragging me around.

00:55.448 --> 00:57.310
But I wasn't the only one
in the family

00:57.310 --> 00:59.172
struggling to gain
independence.

00:59.172 --> 01:00.379
You need to slow down.

01:00.379 --> 01:01.896
I'm barely moving.

01:03.275 --> 01:04.413
Watch out
for that car.

01:04.413 --> 01:05.862
Dad, we're stopped.

01:05.862 --> 01:08.034
In the middle of the street?
At a stop sign!

01:08.034 --> 01:10.344
I know what I'm doing.

01:10.344 --> 01:12.000
Then why aren't
you moving?

01:12.000 --> 01:13.448
It's clear.

01:18.310 --> 01:19.862
[ Sighs ]

01:19.862 --> 01:21.931
Dad, can you
please tell Dean

01:21.931 --> 01:23.344
to stop breathing
on my neck?

01:23.344 --> 01:25.586
That hot breath is gonna
mess up my hair.

01:25.586 --> 01:27.275
Dean, sit back.

01:27.275 --> 01:28.758
Kim, go around this car
in front of you.

01:28.758 --> 01:31.275
Driving like a maniac.

01:31.275 --> 01:32.724
[ Tires screech ]
Be careful, now.

01:32.724 --> 01:33.931
[ Honks horn ]

01:33.931 --> 01:38.758
♪♪

01:38.758 --> 01:40.551
Dad?

01:40.551 --> 01:43.275
Granddaddy Clisby?

01:43.275 --> 01:46.862
The only person I knew
who my dad had to answer to.

01:46.862 --> 01:48.689
Back then,
I thought Granddaddy Clisby

01:48.689 --> 01:50.586
was mean just to be mean.

01:50.586 --> 01:51.862
I was wrong.

01:51.862 --> 01:54.068
That was him being nice.

01:54.068 --> 01:55.448
Mm-hmm.

01:55.448 --> 01:57.517
Yes, Mother Williams.
I can take you.

01:57.517 --> 01:59.827
No problem at all.

01:59.827 --> 02:03.068
Okay. Okay.
Good night.

02:03.068 --> 02:04.586
What's Mama
talking about?

02:04.586 --> 02:06.517
She wants me to take her
to choir practice tomorrow.

02:06.517 --> 02:08.172
She doesn't trust
your dad's driving.

02:08.172 --> 02:09.827
I told you how he was swerving
all over the road.

02:09.827 --> 02:11.758
It was like watching
a drunk turtle.

02:13.620 --> 02:15.137
Well, it was
worse than that.

02:15.137 --> 02:16.482
He had a fender-bender.

02:16.482 --> 02:18.344
Left the car
and walked home.

02:18.344 --> 02:19.758
They called a tow truck,

02:19.758 --> 02:21.172
but he couldn't remember
where he left it.

02:21.172 --> 02:24.103
[ Sighs ]

02:24.103 --> 02:26.000
I guess it's time.

02:26.000 --> 02:27.310
Yeah.

02:27.310 --> 02:29.586
Everybody's time comes
sooner or later.

02:29.586 --> 02:31.413
I know it's hard,

02:31.413 --> 02:33.413
but you're doing
the right thing,

02:33.413 --> 02:35.275
and you're doing it
because you love him.

02:35.275 --> 02:36.689
It's okay, Dad.

02:36.689 --> 02:39.103
He'll be in a better place,
like Buster.

02:39.103 --> 02:41.482
I didn't exactly know
what they were talking about,

02:41.482 --> 02:43.482
but it sounded like
when my dog Buster

02:43.482 --> 02:45.551
had to go to a big farm
in the sky.

02:45.551 --> 02:46.793
What?

02:46.793 --> 02:48.448
Boy, we're talking
about stopping

02:48.448 --> 02:50.482
your granddad from driving,
not putting him down.

02:50.482 --> 02:52.655
Oh!

02:52.655 --> 02:54.068
♪ Oh, oh, oh

02:54.068 --> 02:55.172
♪ And I know

02:55.172 --> 02:56.827
♪ Ohh

02:56.827 --> 02:58.724
♪ Through the highs
and the lows ♪

02:58.724 --> 03:01.827
♪ I'mma find my way home

03:04.758 --> 03:06.724
Bill: It'll be hard at first,
but Lil and I will make sure

03:06.724 --> 03:08.689
you and Mama get every place
you need to go,

03:08.689 --> 03:09.827
on time and in style.

03:09.827 --> 03:11.137
Clisby:
[ Chuckles ]

03:11.137 --> 03:12.793
That's why I was
invited over here.

03:12.793 --> 03:15.379
To fill me up
on pound cake and meat loaf

03:15.379 --> 03:17.655
while you two conspire
to steal my freedom.

03:17.655 --> 03:18.965
No.

03:18.965 --> 03:20.793
W-- [ Sighs ]
We just want you to be safe.

03:20.793 --> 03:22.448
Mm-hmm.
Mother Williams said

03:22.448 --> 03:23.862
you drove into the shed...
Well...

03:23.862 --> 03:25.862
...and crushed all
of her gardening supplies.

03:25.862 --> 03:29.655
I just need to get
my brakes checked, huh?

03:29.655 --> 03:31.310
Listen, why don't you wrap me up
some of this pound cake?

03:31.310 --> 03:32.896
I'm going home.

03:32.896 --> 03:35.275
Mills Brothers on TV tonight,
huh? [ Chuckles ]

03:35.275 --> 03:36.896
Give me your keys.
I'll drive you.

03:36.896 --> 03:39.965
Oh, no, no.
Nobody drives Old Betsy but me.

03:39.965 --> 03:41.655
Come on, Dad.
You know it's for the best.

03:41.655 --> 03:44.724
Best for who?
Not for me.

03:44.724 --> 03:46.931
I mean, h-how am I gonna get
to the barbershop

03:46.931 --> 03:48.206
and see my friends?

03:48.206 --> 03:49.517
He has friends?

03:49.517 --> 03:51.275
Son, now you best get on
out of my way.

03:51.275 --> 03:53.413
Sorry, Daddy,
but this how it has to be.

03:53.413 --> 03:57.724
♪♪

03:57.724 --> 04:00.448
As I watched my dad
face off withhis dad,

04:00.448 --> 04:02.517
I thought how great
it must feel to finally

04:02.517 --> 04:05.241
get to lay down the law
to your own father.

04:05.241 --> 04:07.758
♪♪

04:07.758 --> 04:09.413
But the look
on my dad's face said

04:09.413 --> 04:12.206
it didn't feel great at all.

04:12.206 --> 04:13.965
[ Keys jingle ]

04:17.413 --> 04:19.896
I'mma need to get to
the hardware store on Saturday.

04:19.896 --> 04:21.689
For what?
You have every nail that's --

04:22.620 --> 04:24.689
Fine.
Kim can take you.

04:24.689 --> 04:27.000
As a matter of fact,
you should leave your car
here for her to drive.

04:27.000 --> 04:28.586
Now, how are yougonna
give away mycar?

04:28.586 --> 04:30.413
Really?
I'm getting my own car?

04:30.413 --> 04:32.206
I'll buy it for you,
on the condition

04:32.206 --> 04:34.103
you take your granddaddy
wherever he needs to go.

04:34.103 --> 04:35.862
Hold on. This child don't need
to be driving me all over town.

04:35.862 --> 04:37.379
This child need to be trying
to find herself a husband.

04:37.379 --> 04:40.241
That's what she need --
A husband? She's 17!

04:40.241 --> 04:43.241
Okay, you right.
Ship's passed.

04:43.241 --> 04:45.448
And instead of you
taking Mama to church,
Kim can take her.

04:45.448 --> 04:47.068
But that's
six times a week.
Kim.

04:47.068 --> 04:49.689
This child just got her license
a hot minute ago.

04:49.689 --> 04:51.241
I mean, hell,
I drive better than she do.

04:51.241 --> 04:53.517
She's been trained
by the best -- me.

04:53.517 --> 04:55.275
So it's settled.

04:56.931 --> 04:58.862
This could work out good
for everybody.

04:58.862 --> 05:02.172
Yeah, my dad never got
any better at reading a room.

05:02.172 --> 05:04.896
♪♪

05:04.896 --> 05:06.586
Norman:
The mall was so fun.

05:06.586 --> 05:08.068
The girls from the Catholic
school were there, too.

05:08.068 --> 05:09.758
We all met up in
the parking lot.

05:09.758 --> 05:11.827
Then what'd you do?
Just met up.

05:11.827 --> 05:14.517
I'd never seen them
without their uniforms before.

05:14.517 --> 05:16.517
They were naked?
No, dummy.

05:16.517 --> 05:17.827
They were wearing
regular clothes.

05:17.827 --> 05:19.448
But maybe next time...

05:19.448 --> 05:23.000
Anything could happen
at the mall.

05:23.000 --> 05:26.344
Man, I wish I could go
to the mall without my parents.

05:26.344 --> 05:28.275
How does Norman get
to go by himself?

05:28.275 --> 05:29.379
Divorced dad.

05:29.379 --> 05:31.482
Norm says he lets him
do whatever he wants.

05:31.482 --> 05:34.620
Lucky. Why do my parents gotta
be so in love with each other?

05:34.620 --> 05:36.482
Why isn't there a mall
in your neighborhood?

05:36.482 --> 05:38.275
Oh, you just wait, Brad.

05:38.275 --> 05:41.241
One day that mall by your house
will be the black mall.

05:41.241 --> 05:42.482
It's not fair.

05:42.482 --> 05:44.275
The mall's lousy
with Catholic girls,

05:44.275 --> 05:45.896
and we can't get there.

05:45.896 --> 05:48.172
Well, you guys should
just move closer.

05:48.172 --> 05:51.310
Brad really needed
to watch the news sometimes.

05:51.310 --> 05:53.896
Wait, Norm might be
on to something.

05:53.896 --> 05:56.137
If our dads take us,

05:56.137 --> 05:58.000
they'll probably
just lose us anyway.

05:58.000 --> 06:00.724
That'll give us enough time
to hang out until they find us.

06:00.724 --> 06:02.413
Can your dad take us?

06:02.413 --> 06:04.724
Mm, I mean,
if he's not working late

06:04.724 --> 06:06.758
or going to
a fraternity meeting

06:06.758 --> 06:09.068
or drinking scotch
and listening to jazz.

06:09.068 --> 06:10.758
Maybe your dad
could take us.

06:10.758 --> 06:13.172
Nah, my dad's just gonna say,
"Go with your mother.

06:13.172 --> 06:14.896
She's always shopping."

06:14.896 --> 06:16.689
Then she'll say
it's her money,

06:16.689 --> 06:18.310
she'll spend it
how she wants.

06:18.310 --> 06:20.206
Then they'll send me to my room
so they can talk.

06:20.206 --> 06:21.620
Yeah.

06:21.620 --> 06:22.965
Wait.

06:22.965 --> 06:25.344
There might be
one more option.

06:25.344 --> 06:26.896
Kim just got her license.

06:26.896 --> 06:28.034
Yeah!

06:28.034 --> 06:29.551
Shut up, Brad.
[ Scoffs ]

06:29.551 --> 06:30.896
She'll be paying
even less attention

06:30.896 --> 06:32.034
than our dads would.

06:32.034 --> 06:33.517
We can ditch her easy.

06:33.517 --> 06:35.413
Alright.
Mall, here we come.

06:35.413 --> 06:36.862
[ School bell rings ]

06:36.862 --> 06:38.689
I neglected to mention to Cory

06:38.689 --> 06:42.172
that riding with my sister
came with one condition.

06:42.172 --> 06:43.965
Boy,
stop breathing down my neck.

06:43.965 --> 06:45.620
You're gonna set
my collar on fire.

06:45.620 --> 06:47.172
And comb your hair!

06:47.172 --> 06:48.655
Both of you look
like you got weeds

06:48.655 --> 06:50.172
growing out
of your head.

06:50.172 --> 06:52.448
Our people's hair looked better
during slavery.

06:52.448 --> 06:53.551
I just combed it.

06:53.551 --> 06:55.310
Well, next time,
do it right.

06:55.310 --> 06:57.586
That's how it was
between us and Granddaddy.

06:57.586 --> 07:00.103
I guess he loved his grandkids,
but he never showed it,

07:00.103 --> 07:02.241
just a nonstop
stream of insults.
[ Horn honks ]

07:02.241 --> 07:03.482
Whoa, whoa, whoa, whoa!

07:03.482 --> 07:05.379
Come on, Kim!
Didn't you see the truck?

07:05.379 --> 07:07.206
Maybe if you'd take
some of that eye makeup off,

07:07.206 --> 07:08.862
you could see
a little better.

07:08.862 --> 07:10.379
And criticisms.

07:10.379 --> 07:12.827
I saw him coming up fast,
so I let him pass.

07:12.827 --> 07:14.655
Maybe that's your problem.
You're too nice.

07:14.655 --> 07:18.034
Didn't even cuss at him
or flash a gun.

07:18.034 --> 07:19.862
[ Sighs ]
Okay, Granddaddy.

07:19.862 --> 07:21.758
Next stop is
the hardware store.

07:21.758 --> 07:23.068
Well, you're going
the wrong way.

07:23.068 --> 07:25.793
I'm going to Mercer's
down there on Dexter.

07:25.793 --> 07:27.448
Dean, that's the opposite
way of the mall.

07:27.448 --> 07:29.310
Yeah, Cory's right.
We're gonna miss all the fun.

07:29.310 --> 07:31.931
Why that one?
Aren't all wrenches the same?

07:31.931 --> 07:34.724
Oh, young lady, all you need
to know about tools is

07:34.724 --> 07:37.551
which one to pass your husband
when he's fixing the sink.

07:37.551 --> 07:40.758
The stores on this side of town
don't like us,

07:40.758 --> 07:43.551
so take me to a store
where there's Negro clerks

07:43.551 --> 07:46.620
that don't follow me around
and ask me for my money

07:46.620 --> 07:48.827
just so they can be sure
I can pay.

07:48.827 --> 07:50.965
Okay, but we have to stop
at the grocery store

07:50.965 --> 07:52.275
and the dry cleaner
before we get there.

07:52.275 --> 07:53.655
Dean: No!

07:53.655 --> 07:55.551
Everybody's waiting for us
at the mall.

07:55.551 --> 07:56.931
If we make
all those stops,

07:56.931 --> 07:58.896
they'll be gone
by the time we get there.

07:58.896 --> 08:01.103
If Mercer's sell out
of those new soldering irons,

08:01.103 --> 08:02.862
I'm going to get mean,

08:02.862 --> 08:04.793
and you guys
don't want to see that!

08:04.793 --> 08:07.655
Okay.
Let's listen to some music.

08:07.655 --> 08:09.620
♪ Alright, ow!♪
Oh, my God.

08:09.620 --> 08:11.344
Come on. Come on.
Come on. No.

08:11.344 --> 08:12.827
Yeah, that boy
get too sweaty.

08:12.827 --> 08:14.517
Y'all need to listen
to some gospel.

08:14.517 --> 08:17.206
♪ Yeah, you look to Jesus♪

08:17.206 --> 08:18.620
♪ Look to Jesus♪

08:18.620 --> 08:20.172
♪ Look to Jesus♪

08:20.172 --> 08:22.448
♪ Look to Jesus♪
You two need some Jesus.

08:22.448 --> 08:24.896
Now, son,
I don't know you,

08:24.896 --> 08:27.793
but I can tell by looking at you
that you could use some, too.

08:27.793 --> 08:29.275
[ Scoffs ]

08:29.275 --> 08:31.206
The radio station
is the driver's choice.

08:31.206 --> 08:33.068
♪ Alright♪

08:33.068 --> 08:35.034
Adult Dean: As Kim dragged us
along on her errands,

08:35.034 --> 08:36.931
I discovered
Granddaddy Clisby and I

08:36.931 --> 08:38.379
had something in common.

08:38.379 --> 08:40.275
He hated being
in the Kiddie Car

08:40.275 --> 08:43.482
as much as I hated being
in the Senile Shuttle.

08:43.482 --> 08:45.517
I have Jesus, sir.

08:45.517 --> 08:47.965
Shut up, boy.
You don't.

08:50.103 --> 08:53.310
♪ I got the feeling, baby

08:53.310 --> 08:58.137
♪ Baby, sometimes I'm up

08:58.137 --> 08:59.413
♪ Sometimes I'm down

08:59.413 --> 09:00.827
Is it me,

09:00.827 --> 09:02.931
or does it even
smell like girls in here?

09:02.931 --> 09:05.137
It definitely does.

09:05.137 --> 09:07.413
That's because we're in front of
the perfume department, idiot.

09:07.413 --> 09:09.241
Shh.
Stop talking!

09:09.241 --> 09:11.379
I don't want my friends
to see you here with me.

09:11.379 --> 09:12.862
They think
we're here alone.

09:12.862 --> 09:15.172
Don't disrespect your sister,
hmm.

09:15.172 --> 09:17.241
Do you own a hat?

09:20.931 --> 09:22.758
I was finally able to embark

09:22.758 --> 09:25.241
on my first solo visit
to the mall.

09:25.241 --> 09:30.000
I felt grown, mature, tall...

09:30.000 --> 09:32.068
bored.

09:32.068 --> 09:34.862
None of us knew how
to talk to the girls.

09:34.862 --> 09:37.620
No, that's not how
you walk the dog, Brad.

09:37.620 --> 09:39.689
Here, give me
the yo-yo.

09:39.689 --> 09:42.000
Hey, D.

09:42.000 --> 09:43.103
Ain't that
your girl?

09:43.103 --> 09:45.413
Dean: Charlene.
Hi.

09:45.413 --> 09:47.068
What are you
doing here?

09:47.068 --> 09:49.206
Montgomery Ward got
a new shipment of church hats.

09:49.206 --> 09:51.482
My mom likes to shop before
the other first ladies see them.

09:51.482 --> 09:52.896
Where's your mom?

09:52.896 --> 09:55.206
Uh, at home.

09:55.206 --> 09:57.655
Just hanging out at the mall
with my friends.

09:57.655 --> 09:58.655
Really?

09:58.655 --> 10:00.551
You're so mature.

10:00.551 --> 10:02.413
Want some of this?
Sure.

10:02.413 --> 10:04.724
One of the best things
about having a girlfriend

10:04.724 --> 10:07.827
was that you got
to eat their food.

10:07.827 --> 10:10.034
Uh-oh.

10:10.034 --> 10:11.862
There he is.
Right there.

10:11.862 --> 10:14.103
The only thing more
embarrassing to a teenager

10:14.103 --> 10:16.206
than being seen with parents
in the mall

10:16.206 --> 10:18.275
is being seen with
your grandparents,

10:18.275 --> 10:21.206
especially one as crotchety
as Granddaddy Clisby.

10:21.206 --> 10:23.448
I thought you were
by yourself.

10:23.448 --> 10:26.517
I -- I -- I did.
I -- I was.

10:26.517 --> 10:29.827
Right.
Uh, I'm gonna go find my mom.

10:29.827 --> 10:31.517
See you in church.

10:33.344 --> 10:35.724
I thought we weren't leaving
for two more hours.

10:35.724 --> 10:37.689
We're not, but Granddaddy
didn't want to wait

10:37.689 --> 10:39.482
while I shop for my...

10:39.482 --> 10:40.931
delicates.

10:40.931 --> 10:42.413
Well, now, ladies underwear
ain't no place

10:42.413 --> 10:44.689
for a grown man
to be waiting.

10:44.689 --> 10:46.896
Shouldn't even have
to be looking at it.

10:46.896 --> 10:50.000
Kim, I mean,
if you need some help, I...

10:52.551 --> 10:54.655
He can stay with you
while I finish shopping.

10:54.655 --> 10:55.655
But...

10:55.655 --> 10:57.034
w-we're busy.

10:57.034 --> 10:59.068
Standing around?
He can stand with you.

10:59.068 --> 11:00.068
Bye.

11:00.068 --> 11:01.758
Wait --

11:01.758 --> 11:03.793
Now, these are the boys
you came to the mall to see?

11:03.793 --> 11:05.448
Yes, sir.

11:05.448 --> 11:07.103
Well, I know they make you
go to school with them,

11:07.103 --> 11:09.344
but, uh, you don't have
to pretend to like them,

11:09.344 --> 11:10.448
you understand?

11:10.448 --> 11:11.896
But I dolike them.

11:11.896 --> 11:13.275
Oh, well.

11:13.275 --> 11:15.103
I guess we haveovercome,
then, huh?

11:15.103 --> 11:18.655
Hey, everyone.
Come over here for a minute.

11:18.655 --> 11:21.172
So, this is my granddad,
Mr. Williams.

11:21.172 --> 11:23.172
He's gonna be hanging out
with us for a while.

11:23.172 --> 11:25.586
Yeah, now,
I got a question.

11:25.586 --> 11:27.965
Why would young
and healthy children

11:27.965 --> 11:29.931
want to hang out
in this cold mall

11:29.931 --> 11:32.310
rather than play
in the sunshine outside?

11:32.310 --> 11:34.655
I mean, what's so special
about this place?

11:34.655 --> 11:36.827
Well,
there's a food court.
[ Murmuring agreement ]

11:36.827 --> 11:38.103
Boy, you can
eat at home.

11:38.103 --> 11:39.793
And the movies.

11:39.793 --> 11:43.172
Well, I never was one
for going to the movies.

11:43.172 --> 11:45.482
They used to make us
sit up in the balcony

11:45.482 --> 11:48.241
and see the same shows
that other people got to see

11:48.241 --> 11:49.758
from the good seats.

11:49.758 --> 11:52.965
But your dad used to beg me
and beg me to let him go

11:52.965 --> 11:54.655
so he could be free
with his friends,

11:54.655 --> 11:57.965
but it wasn't safe,
him to be going around and about

11:57.965 --> 12:00.275
where anything
could happen to him.

12:00.275 --> 12:03.241
I began to see why
my dad was so overprotective,

12:03.241 --> 12:05.206
and maybe it
wasn't overprotective.

12:05.206 --> 12:06.655
Maybe it was wise.

12:06.655 --> 12:08.551
Well,
we don't have to sit

12:08.551 --> 12:10.482
in the balcony seats anymore,
Granddad.

12:10.482 --> 12:11.965
Even if we did,

12:11.965 --> 12:14.000
we still don't have money
for the movies.

12:14.000 --> 12:15.586
"Rosemary's Baby"
is playing.

12:15.586 --> 12:17.241
Oh.
I'd love to see that.

12:17.241 --> 12:18.827
Yeah, me too.

12:18.827 --> 12:21.310
But my dad doesn't let me see
R-rated movies.

12:21.310 --> 12:22.758
Your dad said that?

12:22.758 --> 12:25.655
Well, I'm in charge,
and, uh, I got money.

12:25.655 --> 12:26.793
I can get you in.

12:26.793 --> 12:28.482
Really? All of us?

12:28.482 --> 12:30.344
Yeah.

12:30.344 --> 12:32.586
[ All gasp ]

12:32.586 --> 12:33.655
You think this
is enough?

12:33.655 --> 12:35.413
Yeah!

12:35.413 --> 12:37.310
Whenever I looked at
the roll of cash he carried,

12:37.310 --> 12:39.413
I thought Granddaddy Clisby
was rich.

12:39.413 --> 12:41.034
I didn't realize back then,

12:41.034 --> 12:43.172
it was hard for him
to get a bank account.

12:43.172 --> 12:44.551
One good gust of wind,

12:44.551 --> 12:46.344
and he'd be off
to the poorhouse.

12:46.344 --> 12:48.655
Well, I guess we can
get going, then.

12:48.655 --> 12:49.827
Thanks, Mr. Williams.

12:49.827 --> 12:51.068
-Yeah!
-So cool.

12:51.068 --> 12:52.413
This is gonna be so good.

12:52.413 --> 12:53.827
Think we could get
some popcorn, too?

12:53.827 --> 12:55.068
Yes.

12:55.068 --> 12:56.068
Thank you, sir.

12:56.068 --> 12:57.482
Ah.

12:58.689 --> 13:00.344
So, that's who
you're courting now?

13:00.344 --> 13:01.724
What? Oh, no.

13:01.724 --> 13:03.551
I have a girlfriend.
She just left.

13:03.551 --> 13:04.965
[ Chuckles ]
The one with
the cotton candy.

13:04.965 --> 13:07.448
Boy,
if The Blind Boys of Alabama

13:07.448 --> 13:09.275
were standing here,
they'd be singing songs

13:09.275 --> 13:11.137
about how you're looking
at that girl.

13:11.137 --> 13:12.896
Keisa's just my friend.

13:12.896 --> 13:14.793
Ah, well,
whatever you say.

13:14.793 --> 13:17.965
But it was a smart thing
for you to pick a scary movie.

13:17.965 --> 13:20.068
Yeah,
she might get frightened

13:20.068 --> 13:21.517
and let you put
your arm around her.

13:21.517 --> 13:23.379
I like that.

13:23.379 --> 13:25.068
Smart? Wow.

13:25.068 --> 13:26.655
That was the nicest thing

13:26.655 --> 13:28.586
Granddaddy Clisby
had ever said to me.

13:28.586 --> 13:30.689
Maybe he was softening up.

13:30.689 --> 13:33.206
♪♪

13:33.206 --> 13:35.379
That sure was rated R
for a reason.

13:35.379 --> 13:37.586
Oh, please.
You couldn't even see the baby.

13:37.586 --> 13:39.586
Then why is it
still in my head?

13:39.586 --> 13:40.931
I just want my mama.

13:40.931 --> 13:42.896
Don't tell me this movie
scared you kids.

13:42.896 --> 13:44.655
You got to toughen up!

13:44.655 --> 13:46.758
Listen,
when I was 12 years old,

13:46.758 --> 13:49.793
I had already killed a platoon
full of German soldiers

13:49.793 --> 13:50.965
during the Great War.

13:50.965 --> 13:52.758
I shot some of them,

13:52.758 --> 13:54.724
put the bayonet
to the rest of them.

13:54.724 --> 13:56.103
How'd the let you
in the army

13:56.103 --> 13:57.758
if you were still
in junior high?

13:57.758 --> 14:00.448
Because I had a full beard
and a mustache at 11.

14:00.448 --> 14:02.551
[ Laughter ]

14:02.551 --> 14:05.689
You're funny, Granddad.
Thanks for the movie.

14:05.689 --> 14:08.000
Granddad did me such
a huge favor that day.

14:08.000 --> 14:10.793
My friends thought he was cool,
and that made me cool, too.

14:10.793 --> 14:12.517
Let's just keep
this R-rated movie

14:12.517 --> 14:14.655
between the two of us,
alright?

14:14.655 --> 14:15.827
Sorry I'm late.

14:15.827 --> 14:17.137
I ran into a boy
from school

14:17.137 --> 14:18.482
who worked
at the shoe store.

14:18.482 --> 14:20.275
He invited me
to a party,

14:20.275 --> 14:22.000
so I'm gonna have to take you
to the barbershop tomorrow.

14:22.000 --> 14:23.482
Sorry.

14:26.310 --> 14:28.793
Listen, if the Devil is looking
to pick a bride,

14:28.793 --> 14:30.448
I got a suggestion.

14:30.448 --> 14:32.034
[ Both laugh ]

14:32.034 --> 14:34.862
♪♪

14:34.862 --> 14:36.517
Man: [ On television ]
Today we'll be taking a look

14:36.517 --> 14:38.482
at some of our favorite
woodland creatures...

14:38.482 --> 14:40.965
[ Speaking indistinctly ]

14:40.965 --> 14:43.862
♪♪

14:43.862 --> 14:45.310
[ Bottle cap pops ]

14:45.310 --> 14:46.689
Bill.

14:46.689 --> 14:48.551
Bill! [ Chuckles ]

14:48.551 --> 14:51.103
Listen, um,
uh, Kim has left me,

14:51.103 --> 14:52.655
and I needed to get
to the barbershop.

14:52.655 --> 14:53.793
Ah, I'm working on
an arrangement

14:53.793 --> 14:55.000
with Washboard
right now.

14:55.000 --> 14:56.517
We are really smoking!

14:56.517 --> 14:58.034
Give me an hour or so,
and I'll run you home.

14:58.034 --> 15:00.758
N-- B-Bill?

15:00.758 --> 15:02.241
...and other succulent plants.

15:02.241 --> 15:03.517
Be careful...

15:03.517 --> 15:05.172
[ Muttering ]
Nobody tells me...

15:05.172 --> 15:10.551
♪♪

15:10.551 --> 15:13.689
No son of mine is gonna tell me
when I can get my hair cut.

15:15.620 --> 15:17.448
Well, are you
staying or coming?

15:17.448 --> 15:19.000
You want me
to go with you?

15:19.000 --> 15:20.413
Yeah.

15:20.413 --> 15:22.172
Now, now, listen.
Listen, listen.

15:22.172 --> 15:25.000
Now, if you gonna go with me,
no snitching to your dad.

15:25.000 --> 15:26.724
Adult Dean: So it began --

15:26.724 --> 15:28.827
my first joyride
in a stolen vehicle.

15:28.827 --> 15:30.379
Thelma had Louise,

15:30.379 --> 15:33.034
and I had
my 73-year-old grandfather.

15:33.034 --> 15:35.344
We were locked and loaded
for trouble...

15:35.344 --> 15:37.344
as soon as we adjusted
the front seat.

15:37.344 --> 15:38.655
[ Seats squeal, click ]

15:38.655 --> 15:39.896
[ Keys jingle ]

15:39.896 --> 15:41.379
[ Chuckles ]

15:41.379 --> 15:43.137
She didn't know
I had these. Yeah.

15:45.000 --> 15:48.275
You know,
your father, grandmother,

15:48.275 --> 15:49.689
and that redneck
police officer

15:49.689 --> 15:50.931
don't know what
they talking about.

15:50.931 --> 15:53.379
I been driving
for 60 years.

15:53.379 --> 15:55.344
Yeah,
I know what I'm doing.

15:55.344 --> 15:58.034
Watching the expression
on my granddad's face,

15:58.034 --> 16:00.172
I related to him in a new way.

16:00.172 --> 16:02.586
We were both tired
of unfair limitations

16:02.586 --> 16:04.137
other people put on us.

16:04.137 --> 16:06.137
We had both gotten
a taste of independence,

16:06.137 --> 16:07.965
and it was good.

16:07.965 --> 16:09.586
This was actually fun.

16:09.586 --> 16:13.586
The two of us breaking rules,
together.

16:13.586 --> 16:17.551
♪♪

16:17.551 --> 16:18.793
Hey!

16:18.793 --> 16:19.931
How you doing?

16:19.931 --> 16:21.137
Hey there, brother.

16:21.137 --> 16:23.172
Yeah. Good.
Give me that coat.

16:23.172 --> 16:25.482
Oh, Muhammad Ali should have
just gone on into the army.

16:25.482 --> 16:26.965
He'd be back in the ring
by now.

16:26.965 --> 16:28.620
Well, you know what?
I'm glad he took a stand.

16:28.620 --> 16:31.068
And I wish more pro athletes
would, too.

16:31.068 --> 16:33.275
Well, see, I ain't studding
them rich Negroes.

16:33.275 --> 16:37.103
Bring on
the 1968 Summer Olympics.

16:37.103 --> 16:40.275
Real athletes,
no politics.

16:40.275 --> 16:42.482
Okay.
So you don't disagree

16:42.482 --> 16:44.103
with any of this
country's politics?

16:44.103 --> 16:46.793
Son, everybody disagrees
with this country's politics.

16:46.793 --> 16:48.724
You just got to be
ready to serve, see?

16:48.724 --> 16:50.413
I served, hmm?

16:50.413 --> 16:52.241
My son served.

16:52.241 --> 16:55.655
My other grandson
is in Vietnam right now.

16:55.655 --> 16:58.482
You got to be ready
to fight and die for America.

16:58.482 --> 16:59.655
Ain't that right, Dean?

16:59.655 --> 17:00.896
[ Choking ]

17:00.896 --> 17:03.000
Uh, yes. Yes, sir.

17:03.000 --> 17:04.689
Die?[ Chuckles]

17:04.689 --> 17:06.551
I hadn't really thought
about all that.

17:06.551 --> 17:08.482
But that's what the barbershop
was good for --

17:08.482 --> 17:10.413
making you think,
challenging your assumptions,

17:10.413 --> 17:12.137
and giving you a good laugh.

17:12.137 --> 17:14.862
Dean won't take a fastball
for his little league team.

17:14.862 --> 17:17.827
[ Laughter ]
How the hell he ready to die
for his country?

17:17.827 --> 17:20.413
[ Laughter ]

17:20.413 --> 17:23.034
Well, he certainly can't serve
in the army with that hair.

17:23.034 --> 17:25.310
So, Bray, were you able
to do anything with it?

17:25.310 --> 17:26.724
Bray: Well, I trimmed it up.

17:26.724 --> 17:29.655
Now your grandson looks
nice and neat,

17:29.655 --> 17:31.689
like Wicked
Wilson Pickett.

17:31.689 --> 17:33.344
[ Laughter ]

17:33.344 --> 17:36.448
See, you just don't like
the afro style, Mr. Williams.

17:36.448 --> 17:37.689
Okay.

17:37.689 --> 17:39.517
[ Chuckles ]
Come on, Mr. Williams.

17:39.517 --> 17:43.034
Look, you know they say that,
uh, Jesus had hair like wool.

17:43.034 --> 17:44.206
[ Laughter ]

17:44.206 --> 17:45.689
You see,
he's just saying that

17:45.689 --> 17:46.896
because his hair look like

17:46.896 --> 17:49.413
the back end
of a fat sheep's dookey.

17:49.413 --> 17:51.482
[ Laughter ]
Now, that's wrong.

17:51.482 --> 17:54.655
[ Laughter ]

17:54.655 --> 17:57.137
Oh, you laughing hard,
ain't you?

17:57.137 --> 17:59.379
Uh, uh, uh. Game.

17:59.379 --> 18:03.068
[ Laughter ]

18:03.068 --> 18:05.620
Now, now, now, when Bray
first started cutting hair,

18:05.620 --> 18:07.068
oh, he was just
so nervous,

18:07.068 --> 18:09.655
his -- his hands
were shaking like a leaf.

18:09.655 --> 18:11.758
[ Laughs ]
I had to say to him --

18:11.758 --> 18:15.862
I said, "Now, don't you dare cut
no zig-zags in my hair," see?

18:15.862 --> 18:17.103
Granddad!
[ Horn honking ]

18:17.103 --> 18:19.206
[ Tires screech ]

18:22.310 --> 18:24.413
[ Radiator hisses ]

18:26.586 --> 18:28.517
Are you okay?

18:28.517 --> 18:31.034
Yeah, I-I --

18:31.034 --> 18:32.448
I'm fine.

18:32.448 --> 18:34.965
Are you okay?

18:34.965 --> 18:38.137
Yeah, yeah, yeah.
I just...

18:38.137 --> 18:41.241
need a minute
to kind of collect myself.

18:41.241 --> 18:49.620
♪♪

18:49.620 --> 18:52.379
Are you sure
you're okay?

18:52.379 --> 18:55.068
Because I don't know
what I'd do if...

18:55.068 --> 19:01.172
♪♪

19:01.172 --> 19:03.034
But you're okay, right?

19:03.034 --> 19:04.482
Yeah.

19:04.482 --> 19:08.655
♪♪

19:08.655 --> 19:11.000
Damn it!

19:14.275 --> 19:15.758
It's...

19:15.758 --> 19:18.275
just a little accident.

19:18.275 --> 19:22.103
My dad almost ran over
a squirrel last week,

19:22.103 --> 19:24.206
and my mom
was so scared

19:24.206 --> 19:27.758
that she even almost said
a bad word, too.

19:27.758 --> 19:31.103
[ Chuckles ]

19:31.103 --> 19:34.206
Yeah.

19:34.206 --> 19:40.275
♪♪

19:40.275 --> 19:43.379
I learned a lot
about my granddad that day

19:43.379 --> 19:46.103
and why black men like him
go to the barbershop,

19:46.103 --> 19:48.620
even when their hair hasn't
changed in 20 years.

19:48.620 --> 19:50.379
Where you been?
We were so worried!

19:50.379 --> 19:52.275
Look at the car.
Look at the car, Dad.

19:52.275 --> 19:53.793
How many times
do I have to tell you?

19:53.793 --> 19:55.310
I don't know what to tell --
Dean, are you okay?

19:55.310 --> 19:58.620
Are you okay, Dean?
Dad, I don't --

19:58.620 --> 20:03.758
♪♪

20:03.758 --> 20:08.965
♪♪

20:08.965 --> 20:12.068
Watching my granddad deal
with his new situation

20:12.068 --> 20:15.172
made me realize that what
he was being forced to accept

20:15.172 --> 20:16.827
was much harder
than the limitations

20:16.827 --> 20:19.827
I had as a 12-year-old.

20:19.827 --> 20:21.310
I also appreciated

20:21.310 --> 20:24.000
how difficult this was
for my dad

20:24.000 --> 20:26.103
and how difficult
it may be for me one day

20:26.103 --> 20:29.965
when I have to do
the same thing.

20:29.965 --> 20:33.241
Nah! I'm gonna love
telling him what to do.

20:33.241 --> 20:37.000
♪♪

20:37.000 --> 20:39.172
♪ I got my mojo

20:39.172 --> 20:41.862
Younger and older generations
always have more in common

20:41.862 --> 20:43.965
than it appears on the surface.

20:43.965 --> 20:45.413
♪♪

20:45.413 --> 20:48.137
♪ Oh, yeah

20:48.137 --> 20:49.379
♪ I got my mojo

20:49.379 --> 20:51.000
We both want independence,

20:51.000 --> 20:53.103
self-determination...

20:53.103 --> 20:54.758
♪ I'm gonna try it out on you

20:54.758 --> 20:56.379
...and freedom.

20:56.379 --> 20:58.862
♪ Oh, yeah

20:58.862 --> 21:00.344
♪ Well, I tried...

21:00.344 --> 21:02.172
Even if that freedom
doesn't start

21:02.172 --> 21:03.620
until you're down the street,
where your friends

21:03.620 --> 21:05.103
can't see you
getting dropped off.

21:05.103 --> 21:06.379
[ Engine starts ]
♪ Gonna try it on you

21:06.379 --> 21:08.344
Don't worry about it --
All: Ohh!

21:08.344 --> 21:10.586
♪ Well, I tried it
in New York City ♪

21:10.586 --> 21:12.103
[ All shouting ]

21:12.103 --> 21:15.034
♪ Oh, no,
I'm gonna try it on you ♪

21:15.034 --> 21:16.931
♪ Ohhh, yeah
Hey.

21:16.931 --> 21:18.620
Hey!
What's up, Dean?

21:18.620 --> 21:20.517
[ Indistinct conversations ]

21:20.517 --> 21:23.000
-- Captions by VITAC --
